@huitema I'm not sure if that follows the design of RFC 9000.

For frames that can be sent in 0-RTT, RFC 9000 requires endpoints to remember and reuse the value of the Transport Parameters:
> When sending frames in 0-RTT packets, a client MUST only use remembered transport parameters; importantly, it MUST NOT use updated values that it learns from the server's updated transport parameters or from frames received in 1-RTT packets. ([section 7.4.1 of RFC 9000](https://quicwg.org/base-drafts/rfc9000.html#section-7.4.1-12))

One thing to note about the above is that you need to skip all non-ack-eliciting packets that appear immediately after the largest acknowledged packet.  Our stack doesn't individually track whether a received packet is ack-eliciting or not, so our logic isn't perfect in that regard.  I believe you get close though if you increase "largest acknowledged" by one every time the next packet arrives and it isn't ack-eliciting.

Then the logic is fairly simple:

```python
# def on_received(pn):
ranges.add(pn) # Track receipt.

if space != ApplicationData:
    immediate_ack = true
else if pn == ranges.largest.largest:
    # This determines whether there is a gap in the unacknowledged packets.
    if largest_acknowledged < ranges.largest.smallest:
        threshold = loss_threshold
    else:
        threshold = packet_threshold
    immediate_ack = pn > largest_acknowledged + threshold
else if pn < largest_acknowledged:
    immediate_ack = true
else:
    immediate_ack = false

if ack_eliciting:
    if immediate_ack:
        send_ack(now)
    else:
        schedule_ack(now + ack_delay)
else if pn == largest_acknowledged + 1:
    # Disregard this packet for later packet/loss threshold calculations.
    largest_acknowledged = pn
```

I don't know how to implement this.  Or maybe it's just a bug.

Let's say that I acknowledged packet 10.  The packet loss threshold is 4.  As stated, this says: acknowledge immediately if you receive packet 15.  That seems OK.

But if I acknowledge 10, but 9 has not been received, this text implies that receiving 13 would cause an immediate ACK.  That seems like it might always result in an immediate ACK over time:

```
if pn > largest_received:
  largest_received = pn
  for n in 0..(largest_received - loss_threshold):
    if !received(n):
      send_immediate_ack()
      break
```

If instead this is something like:

```
if pn > largest_received:
  largest_received = pn
  if loss_threshold > 0 && largest_received > largest_acked + loss_threshold:
    for n in (largest_acked + 1)..(largest_received - loss_threshold):
      if !received(n):
        send_immediate_ack()
        break
```

That might be a reason to include the largest acknowledged in the calculation.

Assuming the latter is your intent, as this requires iteration over `loss_threshold` packets, receivers should be allowed to limit the size of this value arbitrarily to avoid O(N) work for little attacker cost.

```suggestion
IMMEDIATE_ACK Frame {
```
